So my name is Baldemar.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.240
I help run FurryList, which is a feed

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:19.470
, which is a service that provides feeds for the furry community

00:00:19.470 --> 00:00:19.760
.

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:21.040
And let me see here.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:25.330
I completely forgot how to actually do this.

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:26.340
Right.

00:00:26.340 --> 00:00:27.830
There we go.

00:00:27.890 --> 00:00:29.800
Speaker notes.

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:30.330
Awesome.

00:00:30.470 --> 00:00:31.260
All right.

00:00:31.270 --> 00:00:33.210
So we're good.

00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:37.200
So I have a question for you all.

00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:39.790
Awesome.

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:45.800
So what makes you and me different from strangers?

00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:51.080
So raise your hand if you're a developmental biologist.

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:54.400
Raise your hand if you're a Mexican.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:55.950
And now raise your hand if you care about the open web

00:00:55.950 --> 00:00:56.100
.

00:00:56.100 --> 00:00:57.470
That should be everyone.

00:00:57.470 --> 00:00:57.780
Yeah.

00:00:57.850 --> 00:00:58.090
Okay.

00:00:58.090 --> 00:00:59.060
That's what I thought.

00:00:59.060 --> 00:00:59.890
All right.

00:00:59.900 --> 00:01:06.090
So we have that shared identity and that those shared values.

00:01:06.090 --> 00:01:06.780
Right.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.290
As a and we are sharing this space here as a shared

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:12.820
social space based on those values.

00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:13.390
Right.

00:01:13.390 --> 00:01:18.240
We have that common foundation of trust to build relationships from.

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:23.230
And I'm interested in how exactly we can actually translate those

00:01:24.060 --> 00:01:28.710
relationships into the online space in a way that actually reflects how

00:01:28.710 --> 00:01:31.980
they exist in the real world as they exist.

00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:34.580
And this is what I've kind of been wondering as I

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:36.480
have been helping out with FurryList.

00:01:36.490 --> 00:01:37.480
FurryList.

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:39.870
So if you don't know, FurryList is

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:43.600
a service on Blue Sky that provides feeds for the furry community

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:43.720
.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:45.340
But we don't do a global feed.

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:47.800
And we don't just rely on hashtag feeds.

00:01:47.810 --> 00:01:48.800
Right.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:54.100
What we do is we manually curate every single user that

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:57.630
wants to become a member of our community of our feeds.

00:01:57.630 --> 00:02:01.080
So we've done that for about 64,000 people now

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:01.210
.

00:02:01.220 --> 00:02:04.340
We've started doing that early on in Blue Sky when Ot

00:02:04.350 --> 00:02:07.360
ter was in charge back then othering our founder.

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:11.420
Now Kev has been the lead.

00:02:11.430 --> 00:02:14.160
And we have grown quite a bit since then.

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:17.420
And I'll just show you real quick how it works.

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:19.580
I mean, it's nothing too complicated.

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:21.200
A user follows us, right?

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:25.830
And after that follow, they go into our review backend.

00:02:25.870 --> 00:02:29.900
Now the follow itself is a signal of intentionality, right

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:30.140
?

00:02:30.140 --> 00:02:33.090
They have signal to us that they would like to join our

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:33.750
community.

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:37.160
And our review backend, which looks a little something like this

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:40.360
, is a way for us to check, first off,

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:42.560
whether they are furry.

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:46.030
And second off, whether we believe that they would be a

00:02:46.030 --> 00:02:48.220
good addition to our community.

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:51.620
So there is a manual creation to our community at every level

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:51.860
.

00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:56.160
Every single person within our community has been seen by us.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:59.720
And we have made a manual decision about their belonging within our

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:00.540
community.

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:04.560
Every judgment here is intentional.

00:03:04.570 --> 00:03:07.950
So this is a classic, you know, bi-dire

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:08.650
ctional membership.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:11.250
You know, like the user is part of the community because

00:03:11.270 --> 00:03:12.200
they wish to be.

00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:15.510
And the community allows someone to be part of their community as

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:15.830
well.

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:19.550
This is how most online communities work today, you know?

00:03:20.510 --> 00:03:25.380
But, and when we do this, we actually create what

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:26.960
I'm going to call a trust domain.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:29.590
The user, by being part of, by being part of

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:33.120
the community, implicitly at least initially trusts us to make

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:35.380
good decisions for the community.

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:40.550
And then FurryList then, through this follow record

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:45.090
, says that we believe that they are also a trusted member

00:03:45.130 --> 00:03:46.710
of the community.

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:48.590
And, you know, again, this is how most online

00:03:48.990 --> 00:03:49.720
communities work.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:54.090
But there are a few issues here that I think I've

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:56.530
, that I started to think about.

00:03:56.550 --> 00:04:02.590
Now, the community depends on us for infrastructure and their existence

00:04:02.630 --> 00:04:02.860
.

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:05.730
Now, to be clear, the community is defined through public

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:06.830
records, right?

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:07.360
Like, we follow them.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:09.740
The follow is a public, is a public record.

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:12.990
But we're the ones who provide the feeds for Furry

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:13.370
List.

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:15.360
And this is, but why is that?

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:17.950
Well, let's see, let's go through, uh

00:04:17.950 --> 00:04:21.510
, through what happens when we revoke a record, right

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:21.680
?

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:23.940
I mean, if we revoke a record, then there

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.320
's no proof that we have about.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:28.540
There's no historicity to the community.

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:32.540
When it's gone, it's really difficult to prove that

00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:35.100
you were part of the community at a protocol level.

00:04:35.110 --> 00:04:40.270
And God forbid, if we stop existing, there is no

00:04:40.270 --> 00:04:44.480
proof that the community ever existed in the first place.

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:47.330
There's no history or path forward.

00:04:47.330 --> 00:04:49.420
Everything has to be rebuilt from scratch.

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:51.480
The community itself dissolves.

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:53.100
I mean, this is as if a social media site,

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:54.760
you know, like, were to disappear.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.980
Like, it, you might be able to have a few

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:01.230
friends to find, but the entire social graph itself is gone

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:01.940
, right?

00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:06.050
So, I, I divide these problems into, into two

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:08.120
different domains.

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:11.810
First, the trust service, the trust domain, lives in

00:05:11.890 --> 00:05:13.350
the records that we control.

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:16.550
And if we, and they don't exist independently of us

00:05:16.550 --> 00:05:17.070
, right?

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:20.840
And secondly, there's no easy way to organize, find

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:24.220
, or navigate what others build on our work.

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:26.820
Again, it's not impossible, but it's, but

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:30.060
, but there's no surface through which to find new things

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:30.280
.

00:05:30.290 --> 00:05:34.470
We become the default space, and we don't want to

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:36.600
be the default space.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:39.100
Like, we provide default fees, but we don't want

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:42.510
to do extended governance, uh, uh, because that,

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:46.120
in, in, that enhances the surface through which conflict can

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:47.060
happen with a community.

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:48.060
Right?

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:49.060
We have a limited mandate.

00:05:49.060 --> 00:05:52.050
Our mandate is to vet members of the community.

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:55.480
If we start doing additional governance on top of that, that

00:05:55.480 --> 00:05:58.450
is additional surfaces through which we can come in conflict with the

00:05:58.460 --> 00:05:58.880
community.

00:05:58.890 --> 00:06:02.220
And we put so much effort into, into creating this community

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:02.480
.

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:05.000
We don't want it to go all to waste because of

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.340
a, because of a mistake that we made.

00:06:07.350 --> 00:06:09.670
And, and if, because again, if we make a

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:13.740
mistake and things collapse, it cannot exist independently of us,

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:13.880
right?

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:15.200
These are connected issues.

00:06:15.970 --> 00:06:20.100
Oh, and, um, so thankfully there, the,

00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:22.060
uh, permission that I, I don't, I'm

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:24.320
sure that you, a lot of you guys have been looking

00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:26.610
at, uh, the permission data infrastructure proposal, or,

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:28.400
you know, like rough proposals that it has been doing,

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:30.950
that I think that actually solves one of the issues, uh

00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:32.160
, uh, pretty cleanly.

00:06:32.170 --> 00:06:33.160
And that's ownership.

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:36.990
So essentially we have a, we have a spectrum here from

00:06:36.990 --> 00:06:39.150
private to public data, right?

00:06:39.170 --> 00:06:41.810
The, the, the protocol itself was designed for private,

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:44.620
with, with a public data in mind, and you know

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:47.020
, the extreme end of private data would be end to end

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:47.160
encryption.

00:06:47.170 --> 00:06:49.420
Well, it's two parties who, who, who share

00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:51.100
a, a, a, a, a trust boundary,

00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:54.160
which is probably the smallest trust boundary you can make.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:58.810
Now, permission spaces are things, for example, like a

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:01.390
discord, like a private subreddit or a private forum

00:07:01.390 --> 00:07:02.160
, right?

00:07:02.170 --> 00:07:06.680
These are spaces where there is, uh, where there is

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:09.160
a shared domain of trust.

00:07:09.170 --> 00:07:11.530
Um, you know, like people within the, a discord

00:07:11.530 --> 00:07:14.670
community can see everything within the community, but they can't

00:07:14.690 --> 00:07:16.160
, but people outside of it cannot.

00:07:16.170 --> 00:07:19.030
Um, so this is, I, this I think is

00:07:19.090 --> 00:07:22.950
where the importance, uh, the, the, uh,

00:07:23.130 --> 00:07:27.000
the interesting, uh, like the interesting part for communities lie

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:27.160
.

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:30.790
And when thinking about, uh, when thinking about ownership of

00:07:30.790 --> 00:07:33.950
these trust domains, I think that the, that, uh

00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:36.550
, that blue sky has come up with, uh, uh

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:38.160
, a correct solution.

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:40.490
So here again, bi-directional follows, uh,

00:07:40.490 --> 00:07:42.610
each record here lives in the, in, uh, in

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:45.720
each author's repository, which is, you know, how

00:07:45.720 --> 00:07:47.150
follow records typically work.

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:50.950
However, uh, within the permission data infrastructure draft so far

00:07:50.960 --> 00:07:54.780
, there is a sign at the station that the ACL maintain

00:07:54.780 --> 00:07:57.090
er, the access control list maintainer, writes to the

00:07:57.110 --> 00:08:00.160
, to the user's, um, uh, repository.

00:08:00.170 --> 00:08:03.400
This is signed and this is verifiable independently of whether the

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:05.150
ACL maintainer wants to or not.

00:08:05.170 --> 00:08:07.160
And it lives in the user's repository.

00:08:07.170 --> 00:08:09.160
It exists independently, right?

00:08:09.170 --> 00:08:12.640
So this becomes in a way a historical fact, even if

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:16.160
, even if there is a retraction of the credential,

00:08:16.190 --> 00:08:20.410
um, this, uh, this credential still exists and it

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:23.030
exists independently of the ACL maintainer.

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:25.800
Um, now let's think about what furry list does today

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:28.630
, uh, compared to the ACL maintainer in the permission

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:29.160
spec.

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:35.160
So we curate a membership list.

00:08:35.170 --> 00:08:36.160
They also curate a membership list.

00:08:36.170 --> 00:08:37.160
We do vetting.

00:08:37.170 --> 00:08:39.160
They also have to do vetting of some kind.

00:08:39.170 --> 00:08:41.160
Uh, we use followbacks as proofs.

00:08:41.170 --> 00:08:43.160
Credentials in this scenario are proof.

00:08:43.170 --> 00:08:45.160
We use unfollows as removals.

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:47.160
You can also do credential withdrawals.

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:48.960
Stop admitting, uh, uh, by, you know,

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:50.150
not issuing any new ones.

00:08:50.170 --> 00:08:52.160
We already kind of act like an ACL.

00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:55.150
We just don't issue any credentials yet.

00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:58.030
So this is the, this is, uh, how things

00:08:58.030 --> 00:09:02.160
existed before, you know, again, no historicity.

00:09:02.170 --> 00:09:05.950
But think about how things look when we actually use these ver

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:09.160
ifiable, uh, these verifiable credentials.

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:13.230
A retraction really is not, uh, like, it

00:09:13.230 --> 00:09:16.160
, it, it's not an erasure.

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:18.640
I think about it kind of like how, uh, you

00:09:18.650 --> 00:09:21.090
know, like, uh, uh, a scientific journal retract

00:09:21.090 --> 00:09:22.160
s a paper.

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:24.160
A retraction is a statement that says, we made a

00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:24.160
mistake.

00:09:24.170 --> 00:09:26.580
We no longer believe, uh, this statement that we made

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:27.150
is true.

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:29.160
But the paper's still available.

00:09:29.170 --> 00:09:30.160
Similar here.

00:09:30.170 --> 00:09:31.160
It's a statement.

00:09:31.170 --> 00:09:33.160
Like a labeler, right?

00:09:33.170 --> 00:09:36.160
Um, the, the history of the decision is preserved.

00:09:36.170 --> 00:09:40.160
And the governance that results from it becomes auditable.

00:09:40.170 --> 00:09:44.750
And if we disappear, um, in theory, the,

00:09:44.750 --> 00:09:48.690
the, the, the history of the community survives.

00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:50.160
Because the credentials still exist.

00:09:50.170 --> 00:09:52.160
They exist within the user repository.

00:09:52.170 --> 00:09:55.280
And in theory, a path to credential, uh, to

00:09:55.280 --> 00:09:57.150
recovery is possible.

00:09:57.170 --> 00:10:02.150
But the important part is that it's possible.

00:10:02.170 --> 00:10:04.670
That does not mean that it is, uh, that,

00:10:04.670 --> 00:10:06.160
that it will happen.

00:10:06.170 --> 00:10:11.940
Without a structure to reorganize around, without a matrix that

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:14.930
, that, that the community exists in, the community still

00:10:15.110 --> 00:10:16.160
becomes a diaspora, right?

00:10:16.170 --> 00:10:18.730
If we're just defined by the, by, by the

00:10:18.730 --> 00:10:20.880
ACL, then we're still back to the, to square

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:21.160
one.

00:10:21.170 --> 00:10:22.160
If we disappear.

00:10:22.170 --> 00:10:23.160
And if our feeds disappear, right?

00:10:23.170 --> 00:10:25.160
There's nothing to reorganize around.

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:29.780
Now, we, I think that credential solves the first part

00:10:29.780 --> 00:10:31.160
pretty nicely.

00:10:31.170 --> 00:10:32.160
But what about the second part?

00:10:32.170 --> 00:10:34.160
What about the structure itself?

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:36.980
So to do this, I would like to, uh,

00:10:37.010 --> 00:10:40.640
talk about one of my, uh, favorite feeds, which

00:10:40.670 --> 00:10:41.160
is the science feed.

00:10:41.170 --> 00:10:44.490
And in many ways, the science feed, um, it

00:10:44.490 --> 00:10:47.160
does similar work to furry list.

00:10:47.170 --> 00:10:51.160
The science feed, uh, manually checks orchids.

00:10:51.170 --> 00:10:53.950
They do staff page, page checks to check whether, uh

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:56.210
, something is, uh, uh, whether an account is

00:10:56.220 --> 00:10:57.160
associated with a professor.

00:10:57.170 --> 00:10:59.160
They check publication lists.

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:01.680
They really do the field work, uh, to, to

00:11:01.680 --> 00:11:05.160
verify whether someone is part of their, of, uh,

00:11:05.160 --> 00:11:07.160
their, you know, scientific community.

00:11:07.170 --> 00:11:11.480
This has created, like, an extraordinary trust surface of thousands

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:14.160
and thousands of real world scientists.

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:16.320
It, it, it, it really is just an incredible

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:19.150
undertaking, what they have been able to make here.

00:11:19.170 --> 00:11:22.550
But, like, think about, like, what results from

00:11:22.550 --> 00:11:23.160
this.

00:11:23.170 --> 00:11:26.140
It's just one feed.

00:11:26.170 --> 00:11:28.160
And it's good feed.

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:29.160
And I love using that feed.

00:11:29.170 --> 00:11:31.160
But a feed is not a space.

00:11:31.170 --> 00:11:35.160
It's a one of many different conversations that can happen.

00:11:35.170 --> 00:11:36.660
I mean, I want to talk, you know, I

00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:38.150
'm a developmental biologist.

00:11:38.170 --> 00:11:40.140
I want to talk about, like, some help with,

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:42.160
like, my zebrafish experiments.

00:11:42.170 --> 00:11:43.160
Or how to use a particular microscope.

00:11:43.170 --> 00:11:44.160
Or help with grant proposals.

00:11:44.170 --> 00:11:45.160
Things like that.

00:11:45.170 --> 00:11:48.160
This would be an amazing trust surface to use it on.

00:11:48.170 --> 00:11:51.030
Because I know that the people that are here know what they

00:11:51.030 --> 00:11:52.160
're talking about.

00:11:52.170 --> 00:11:55.140
But there's nothing there to go to.

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:57.160
And it's not because of the protocol.

00:11:57.170 --> 00:12:01.160
The, like, this is publicly accessible.

00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:03.160
You can make it, technically.

00:12:03.170 --> 00:12:04.600
And, you know, like, you can make that space

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:05.160
if you wish.

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:07.160
But there is no way to find it.

00:12:07.170 --> 00:12:08.160
Right?

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:10.160
There's no way to, to, to find.

00:12:10.170 --> 00:12:13.150
There's no way to find what has been built off of

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:15.150
this infrastructure here.

00:12:15.170 --> 00:12:18.160
No matrix through which the community itself can exist.

00:12:18.170 --> 00:12:21.150
Apart from what the maintainer itself provides.

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:24.140
So, why does this happen?

00:12:24.170 --> 00:12:28.880
I think this is because of something that we should all be

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:30.160
familiar here.

00:12:30.170 --> 00:12:32.160
When we think about the app protocol.

00:12:32.170 --> 00:12:35.150
And that's the tendency towards centralization.

00:12:35.170 --> 00:12:37.160
People want to be where the people are.

00:12:37.170 --> 00:12:38.160
You know?

00:12:38.170 --> 00:12:42.160
Like, distribution is not a good user experience.

00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:44.160
During the beginning there were many.

00:12:44.170 --> 00:12:47.500
But, because everyone wants to be in one place where everyone

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:48.160
else is.

00:12:48.170 --> 00:12:51.150
Everything converges to one maintainer.

00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:52.160
The landlord.

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:55.240
Same thing that happened with, you know, like, you

00:12:55.240 --> 00:12:56.160
know, the online social web as well.

00:12:56.170 --> 00:12:58.550
Everything converges to one because people want to be where the

00:12:58.550 --> 00:12:59.150
people are.

00:12:59.170 --> 00:13:00.160
You know?

00:13:00.170 --> 00:13:02.090
And I think, I think that a lot of people kind

00:13:02.090 --> 00:13:03.150
of ask the question.

00:13:03.170 --> 00:13:05.160
Like, how can we fight this?

00:13:05.170 --> 00:13:08.780
I don't think that this is really something that we can

00:13:08.780 --> 00:13:10.150
or should fight.

00:13:10.170 --> 00:13:13.150
It's not a good user experience to do so.

00:13:13.170 --> 00:13:16.500
Blue Sky and the app protocol so far has been successful precisely

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:17.160
because it doesn't fight it.

00:13:17.170 --> 00:13:18.160
You know?

00:13:18.170 --> 00:13:20.910
Blue Sky itself, you know, is the entryway into

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:22.160
the app protocol.

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:25.350
But it does not make you make a choice about which app

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:26.160
you will use.

00:13:26.170 --> 00:13:28.730
Because Blue Sky is the default and it's what everyone else

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:29.150
uses.

00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:33.220
And from there you can make the choice to exit if you

00:13:33.220 --> 00:13:34.150
want to.

00:13:34.170 --> 00:13:36.340
I think that we can do something similar if we, with

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:37.150
communities.

00:13:37.170 --> 00:13:43.160
By giving that centralizing force a limited mandate.

00:13:43.170 --> 00:13:46.150
And by making community infrastructure independent, like credentials.

00:13:46.170 --> 00:13:53.160
And then make community infrastructure discoverable from the community definition.

00:13:53.170 --> 00:13:57.160
From what something like furry list creates.

00:13:57.170 --> 00:14:02.150
So, if we allow members of a community to say,

00:14:02.150 --> 00:14:04.160
define a government social space.

00:14:04.170 --> 00:14:06.160
Which I'm going to call a venue here.

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:08.160
Through some kind of record.

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:15.160
Then that record becomes a link between the infrastructure of the community

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:15.160
.

00:14:15.170 --> 00:14:17.160
And the definition of the community.

00:14:17.170 --> 00:14:19.160
The credentials of the community.

00:14:19.170 --> 00:14:22.150
And this opens up a ton of affordances.

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:27.150
Governance now, has a surface for disagreement.

00:14:27.170 --> 00:14:30.150
There's two governances here, right?

00:14:30.170 --> 00:14:32.160
There's not just the one governance for us.

00:14:32.170 --> 00:14:35.150
Which means that if we make, if we make a mistake

00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:35.160
.

00:14:35.170 --> 00:14:36.160
Or something the community disagrees with.

00:14:36.170 --> 00:14:39.150
There is a surface here through which that disagreement can surface.

00:14:39.170 --> 00:14:41.160
And be absorbed.

00:14:41.170 --> 00:14:42.160
Not necessarily the member level.

00:14:42.170 --> 00:14:45.150
But at the actual spaces where people exist.

00:14:45.170 --> 00:14:49.160
And this can create back pressure.

00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:54.370
So, the relationship between these two is now surfaceable at

00:14:54.370 --> 00:14:56.160
a protocol level.

00:14:56.170 --> 00:14:59.140
Which means that apps.

00:14:59.170 --> 00:15:01.160
And app user apps.

00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:04.140
Can surface this connection.

00:15:04.170 --> 00:15:06.160
Between the community infrastructure.

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:08.160
And the community definition itself.

00:15:08.170 --> 00:15:15.160
And because this is emergent from the community itself.

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:16.160
And the community members.

00:15:16.170 --> 00:15:19.140
Plurality kind of becomes the norm.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:22.030
There are many spaces that are run by self-select

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:23.160
ed stewards.

00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:27.420
Who have decided they care enough about the community to create these

00:15:27.420 --> 00:15:28.150
spaces.

00:15:28.170 --> 00:15:32.100
That create, that create like different spaces for different needs for

00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:33.150
the community.

00:15:33.170 --> 00:15:35.160
With different types of governances.

00:15:35.170 --> 00:15:40.750
And members can use the ones that they resonate with the most

00:15:40.750 --> 00:15:41.160
.

00:15:41.170 --> 00:15:44.150
And this topology emerges from the users.

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:47.150
It does not emerge from, you know, furry lists.

00:15:47.170 --> 00:15:49.160
Or, you know, whoever defines the community itself.

00:15:49.170 --> 00:15:54.620
The credential is opening up all of these, all of these

00:15:54.620 --> 00:15:56.150
different, all of these different spaces.

00:15:56.170 --> 00:15:59.150
A single community can have different spaces.

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:01.160
Run by different operators.

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:02.160
Different governances.

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:05.150
And yet they all here share a trust domain.

00:16:05.170 --> 00:16:10.150
Where the credential is the unifying factor.

00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:15.630
And users then can, you know, route their posts to

00:16:15.630 --> 00:16:16.160
different places.

00:16:16.170 --> 00:16:19.270
Through, for example, if this, if they're defined

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:20.160
by a record.

00:16:20.170 --> 00:16:22.160
TID as metadata.

00:16:22.170 --> 00:16:23.160
Let's say, for example.

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:26.540
It could, might as well just be like a random hashtag

00:16:26.540 --> 00:16:28.150
at the end of the post.

00:16:28.170 --> 00:16:31.140
And this can be used as metadata.

00:16:31.170 --> 00:16:34.150
As information that defines a space within the public network.

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:35.160
Right?

00:16:35.170 --> 00:16:38.140
Because the metadata is unique.

00:16:38.170 --> 00:16:40.160
And it does not convey any information.

00:16:40.170 --> 00:16:43.150
The information emerges from how people use it.

00:16:43.170 --> 00:16:46.370
And this is actually something that I would like to, that

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:49.160
I like to shout out for, with Nighthaven.

00:16:49.170 --> 00:16:51.870
Who's a Blue Sky fellow, I believe, has done

00:16:51.870 --> 00:16:55.160
some good work in, in kind of exploring this area.

00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:57.160
He calls it a mezzanine.

00:16:57.170 --> 00:16:59.190
They call it a mezzanine, which I think

00:16:59.190 --> 00:17:01.160
it's a, is a really apt description.

00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:03.270
Because a mezzanine is, is, shares a

00:17:03.290 --> 00:17:05.160
space with the ground floor.

00:17:05.170 --> 00:17:07.160
But there's an intentionality to going up there.

00:17:07.170 --> 00:17:09.420
There's a, it's a shared frequency where people can

00:17:09.480 --> 00:17:10.150
congregate.

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:13.150
That still exists within the public network.

00:17:13.170 --> 00:17:17.160
So, it exists kind of like this.

00:17:17.170 --> 00:17:20.730
You know, like, because these all are, are connected

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:24.160
through the, through the community definition.

00:17:24.170 --> 00:17:28.160
Each one is independently, either independently operated.

00:17:28.170 --> 00:17:31.220
So they are separate governances, separate stewards, but are

00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:32.160
all connected.

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:34.630
So, this is what, this is what it could look

00:17:34.630 --> 00:17:35.150
like.

00:17:35.170 --> 00:17:37.950
You know, the roster kind of gives, the roster gives

00:17:37.950 --> 00:17:40.150
out credentials to the community members.

00:17:40.170 --> 00:17:42.230
The, the, the, the, they can make venues

00:17:42.230 --> 00:17:45.840
through which, through which members can then self sort and use

00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:48.160
the ones that they resonate with the most.

00:17:48.170 --> 00:17:54.120
And, yeah, each node in this graph is an independent

00:17:54.120 --> 00:18:00.200
agent that has complete, complete independence and complete agency within their

00:18:00.200 --> 00:18:01.160
own domains.

00:18:01.170 --> 00:18:04.150
But cannot, cannot directly affect the others.

00:18:04.170 --> 00:18:08.380
But they can affect the others collectively through back pressure from the

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:09.150
bottom up.

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:11.880
For example, if a venue, you know, if a

00:18:11.880 --> 00:18:14.880
venue's governance acts badly, well, they're operating in

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:16.160
a public network with public data, right?

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:19.140
So, they can make a different one.

00:18:19.170 --> 00:18:21.680
And they don't have to make a different one in order

00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:23.160
to change the governance.

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:27.880
But the mere threat that they could influences venues to act in

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:31.160
accordance to what the community wants, right?

00:18:31.170 --> 00:18:33.160
That is a back pressure mechanism of action.

00:18:33.170 --> 00:18:35.160
And this also works for the roster.

00:18:35.170 --> 00:18:38.800
If the roster makes a bad decision, if they admit someone

00:18:38.800 --> 00:18:42.570
they shouldn't have, or they, if they admit someone

00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:44.520
they shouldn't have, or they retract trust from someone that

00:18:44.520 --> 00:18:47.950
they shouldn't have, each individual venue here can override that

00:18:47.950 --> 00:18:51.160
decision and say, you made a bad decision.

00:18:51.170 --> 00:18:53.760
And if this happens throughout the community, that is a back

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:56.910
pressure mechanism saying, you are doing, you're, like

00:18:56.910 --> 00:18:58.160
, you were wrong.

00:18:58.170 --> 00:19:00.160
The community disagrees with you.

00:19:00.170 --> 00:19:03.150
It is layered back pressure mechanisms.

00:19:03.170 --> 00:19:06.150
So, are we done here?

00:19:06.170 --> 00:19:07.160
I guess we're done here.

00:19:07.170 --> 00:19:09.160
I guess I can just go home.

00:19:09.170 --> 00:19:11.160
Oh, right.

00:19:11.930 --> 00:19:18.500
So, communities cannot simply exist in public, especially when they

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:20.150
share a trust boundary.

00:19:20.170 --> 00:19:22.890
This is, it is a problem to exist only in public

00:19:22.890 --> 00:19:24.160
for communities.

00:19:24.170 --> 00:19:27.150
If everything is surface level, there's little opportunity for depth

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:28.160
of conversation.

00:19:28.170 --> 00:19:31.440
Even if, in the science community, we have created this

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:34.160
amazing, this amazing surface of trust.

00:19:34.170 --> 00:19:36.980
But there's little meaningful way to take advantage of it if

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:39.150
every conversation happens in public.

00:19:39.170 --> 00:19:40.160
You know?

00:19:40.170 --> 00:19:44.840
Every interaction within these spaces is done in front of imagined audiences

00:19:44.840 --> 00:19:45.150
.

00:19:45.170 --> 00:19:48.150
People who you think might be looking at.

00:19:48.170 --> 00:19:52.840
And that depth, that community depth, I believe, is

00:19:52.840 --> 00:19:59.170
important to really take the full advantage of this trust that we

00:19:59.250 --> 00:20:00.160
're building.

00:20:00.170 --> 00:20:02.910
And, you know, like I said, with the permission

00:20:02.910 --> 00:20:07.140
data system that Blue Sky is building, we're already acting

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:09.140
kind of like an ACL.

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:13.220
So, then the question becomes, like, what if we

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:16.160
just become the ACL maintainer?

00:20:16.170 --> 00:20:20.610
What if we just become, like, the system that decides

00:20:20.610 --> 00:20:25.140
who does and does not gain access to permission data?

00:20:25.170 --> 00:20:29.030
Well, this means that not only could posts be made public

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:36.160
or private to our community, but because venues exist as defined

00:20:36.160 --> 00:20:40.350
as records, individual venues can also be either public or private

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:43.160
or even individual subspaces within them.

00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:48.150
The outside might see all of First Sky.

00:20:48.170 --> 00:20:50.880
They might see some of the fursuit maker spaces if

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:53.420
there's, you know, like a sale going on for

00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:55.150
, like, a fursuit or something like that.

00:20:55.170 --> 00:20:58.200
But they don't see it all unless you're part of

00:20:58.210 --> 00:21:01.160
the permission space of the community.

00:21:01.170 --> 00:21:03.980
Once you're in this permission space, you can see,

00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:06.650
for example, that Bafers exists or that Stem

00:21:06.650 --> 00:21:08.640
fers exists, who did not want to share what they

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:10.150
were talking about in public.

00:21:10.170 --> 00:21:13.140
You can join in with the advice for fursuit makers

00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:14.640
and see, you know, learn how to make a f

00:21:14.640 --> 00:21:16.710
ursuit for yourself or the fursuit, you know

00:21:16.710 --> 00:21:20.160
, if you don't have any experience with it.

00:21:20.170 --> 00:21:22.680
Even within these boundaries, you can create another one if you

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:23.150
so wish.

00:21:23.170 --> 00:21:25.420
You can create another roster that's just for, like,

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:27.160
for example, Furryless moderators.

00:21:27.170 --> 00:21:36.030
And this is just simple set logic, right

00:21:36.740 --> 00:21:37.160
?

00:21:37.170 --> 00:21:39.160
The design space is modular.

00:21:39.170 --> 00:21:41.920
And any kind of set logic here is possible because, I

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:44.150
mean, we have the fundamentals here.

00:21:44.170 --> 00:21:45.160
We have the boundaries.

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:47.160
And we have the spaces within them.

00:21:47.170 --> 00:21:52.730
So, however, if you're thinking about how efficient data

00:21:52.730 --> 00:21:57.160
system would work here, you might have noticed something.

00:21:57.170 --> 00:22:02.150
If the roster here has full control over the community's ACL

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:05.600
and their permission data, and it can revoke protocol-

00:22:05.600 --> 00:22:08.250
level access to the community data, then it's kind of

00:22:08.300 --> 00:22:12.150
acting like what the landlord was acting like, right?

00:22:12.170 --> 00:22:15.150
They have full control over the community's permission data.

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:18.890
So, haven't we just recreated the landlord, essentially

00:22:18.890 --> 00:22:19.160
?

00:22:19.170 --> 00:22:23.880
And this is where I think the at protocol can really help

00:22:23.890 --> 00:22:28.030
, not necessarily at the protocol level, but in the ability

00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:30.160
to go off protocol.

00:22:30.170 --> 00:22:33.970
So, say that we at Furryless retract that credential

00:22:34.060 --> 00:22:35.150
for someone.

00:22:35.170 --> 00:22:37.960
We say that we no longer trust them as a member of

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:39.160
our community.

00:22:39.170 --> 00:22:42.030
As a result, they lose protocol-level access to the

00:22:42.030 --> 00:22:43.160
community data.

00:22:43.170 --> 00:22:45.000
There is no fix for this, and I don't think

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:46.150
that there should be.

00:22:46.170 --> 00:22:50.320
But let's say that a single venue disagrees, in

00:22:50.320 --> 00:22:51.160
this case, Furseumakis.

00:22:51.170 --> 00:22:53.160
They're governed and still vouches for them.

00:22:53.170 --> 00:22:55.160
They still think that they were a valuable member of their community

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:57.160
and that we were too harsh in their decisions.

00:22:57.170 --> 00:23:00.150
At the protocol level, there is no fixing this.

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:04.680
But consider what happens when these live in an app, an

00:23:04.680 --> 00:23:12.160
app that must govern or moderate what happens within them, you

00:23:12.160 --> 00:23:12.160
know?

00:23:12.170 --> 00:23:15.150
Then something interesting can happen.

00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:18.470
If Furseumakis can send a voucher signal within

00:23:18.470 --> 00:23:22.010
this permission space and the app view has access to that space

00:23:22.130 --> 00:23:27.310
, then the app view can act as a mediator of

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:29.030
that venue's governance.

00:23:29.170 --> 00:23:31.620
They can say, well, yes, we have access to

00:23:31.620 --> 00:23:34.290
all of this and the roster says, you know, that

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:36.160
they do no longer trust them.

00:23:36.170 --> 00:23:41.910
But in this particular social space, in this particular governance space

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:45.140
, they still trust them.

00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:48.940
So we can still serve that content to that user and allow

00:23:48.940 --> 00:23:52.160
them to interact in this particular space.

00:23:52.170 --> 00:23:54.160
But only in that space.

00:23:54.170 --> 00:23:57.150
It's a window into the permission space.

00:23:57.170 --> 00:24:01.160
And it only exists outside of the protocol.

00:24:01.170 --> 00:24:06.590
It exists because the app view is the trusted mediator of

00:24:06.600 --> 00:24:10.140
governance between all of these.

00:24:10.170 --> 00:24:15.150
So this is the system that I call composable trust.

00:24:15.170 --> 00:24:20.150
Each role here, each part here has a particular role.

00:24:20.170 --> 00:24:25.150
The roster can issue -- decides who belongs.

00:24:25.170 --> 00:24:28.500
But it does not decide what the community looks like or how

00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:30.150
they govern themselves.

00:24:30.170 --> 00:24:33.150
The venue can govern their space.

00:24:33.170 --> 00:24:36.850
They can design their space and set the rules and set what

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:38.150
the space is about.

00:24:38.170 --> 00:24:41.150
But they can't yield -- they can't make credentials.

00:24:41.170 --> 00:24:46.150
They have to define themselves based on an existing community definition.

00:24:46.170 --> 00:24:49.850
The app view assembles the view, enforces -- enfor

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:54.160
ces the ACL, enforces trust, mediates trust,

00:24:54.170 --> 00:24:56.160
mediates the venues governance.

00:24:56.170 --> 00:24:58.160
But it holds no data.

00:24:58.170 --> 00:25:00.160
It cannot make -- it does not make credentials.

00:25:00.170 --> 00:25:03.150
It has no governance authority in and of itself.

00:25:03.170 --> 00:25:07.500
It's powerful, but it's still replaceable, just

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:09.160
as the rest of these.

00:25:09.170 --> 00:25:12.890
And the members themselves are the ones who hold all the cards

00:25:12.890 --> 00:25:13.160
.

00:25:13.170 --> 00:25:14.160
They own the data.

00:25:14.170 --> 00:25:16.160
They hold the credentials.

00:25:16.170 --> 00:25:19.150
They choose which community definitions to be a part of.

00:25:19.170 --> 00:25:21.420
And within those community definitions, within that trust domain, they

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:23.160
choose where they want to be.

00:25:23.170 --> 00:25:28.160
And each role here is auditable by the others.

00:25:28.170 --> 00:25:32.590
And each one is replaceable without destroying the rest, without

00:25:32.930 --> 00:25:34.160
destroying the community.

00:25:35.170 --> 00:25:40.150
So compare this to how platforms and online communities exist nowadays.

00:25:40.170 --> 00:25:42.160
The platform is at the top.

00:25:42.170 --> 00:25:44.160
They control everything below.

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:47.760
The admin for a particular space -- it's usually one person

00:25:47.760 --> 00:25:52.070
that controls the space -- is in control of the entire governed

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:53.150
space.

00:25:53.170 --> 00:25:57.440
The mods -- they might delegate some authority, you know,

00:25:57.440 --> 00:25:58.150
to the mods.

00:25:58.170 --> 00:26:01.150
They're still ultimately at the discretion of the admin.

00:26:01.170 --> 00:26:03.160
And the users are at the very bottom.

00:26:03.170 --> 00:26:07.440
They are at -- their existence within this space is at the

00:26:07.440 --> 00:26:09.160
discretion of all the layers above.

00:26:09.170 --> 00:26:13.160
And if one of these fails, everything below it fails.

00:26:13.170 --> 00:26:16.150
Now consider how this system works.

00:26:16.170 --> 00:26:19.150
This is now a system of roles and relationships.

00:26:19.170 --> 00:26:23.780
The community structure itself emerges from the bottom up from the users

00:26:23.780 --> 00:26:24.150
.

00:26:24.170 --> 00:26:27.910
Each node here is -- can be audited by the others

00:26:27.910 --> 00:26:28.160
.

00:26:28.170 --> 00:26:31.940
If any one of these systems violates the community's trust

00:26:31.940 --> 00:26:34.160
, they can be replaced.

00:26:34.170 --> 00:26:38.760
And if these relationships are surfaced well, if the community

00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:43.030
structure is navigable, then the community can survive any one

00:26:43.030 --> 00:26:45.150
single failure of these.

00:26:45.170 --> 00:26:49.160
Nobody here holds all the power for a community.

00:26:49.170 --> 00:26:53.800
The community is built from the bottom up by the people that

00:26:53.800 --> 00:26:55.160
inhabit it.

00:26:55.170 --> 00:26:58.970
So I think that -- I think that this is a good

00:26:59.070 --> 00:27:01.160
structure for a solution.

00:27:01.170 --> 00:27:05.160
Remember this -- this diagram that I showed you here?

00:27:05.170 --> 00:27:07.160
So this is what a single community looks like.

00:27:07.170 --> 00:27:10.150
This is what for realists might look like.

00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:12.160
But consider what this could be.

00:27:12.170 --> 00:27:14.160
This is what communities could look like.

00:27:14.170 --> 00:27:18.610
A navigable trust graph with overlapping affinities, overlapping

00:27:18.610 --> 00:27:23.830
relationships that gives structure to communities in a way that no platform

00:27:23.830 --> 00:27:26.160
, no AI, no algorithm could make.

00:27:26.170 --> 00:27:30.320
Because it is built from the bottom up by the community and

00:27:30.320 --> 00:27:31.150
who they trust.

00:27:31.170 --> 00:27:36.020
This is a trust graph that is built by all and owned

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:37.160
by none.

00:27:37.170 --> 00:27:41.430
So if you would like to help build this, I have

00:27:41.430 --> 00:27:45.160
a -- I have a more technical proposal up on Leaflet

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:48.150
if you're interested in reading that.

00:27:48.170 --> 00:27:51.800
Otherwise, if you are interested in helping build these kinds of

00:27:51.810 --> 00:27:54.160
sustainable communities, please do reach out.

00:27:54.170 --> 00:27:56.160
I mean, I'm super interested.

00:27:56.170 --> 00:27:59.150
I'm hoping to get some schemas out after this conference

00:27:59.160 --> 00:28:03.160
and start building something -- something real.

00:28:03.170 --> 00:28:08.290
I'm not a coder, but I'm really excited

00:28:08.290 --> 00:28:13.630
to see what we can make with this infrastructure and with the

00:28:13.680 --> 00:28:14.160
protocol.

00:28:14.170 --> 00:28:15.160
Yeah.

00:28:15.170 --> 00:28:16.160
Thank you.

00:28:16.170 --> 00:28:17.160
Is this on?

00:28:17.170 --> 00:28:18.160
Ooh.

00:28:18.170 --> 00:28:19.160
Thank you so much.

00:28:19.170 --> 00:28:20.160
Baldemar.

00:28:20.170 --> 00:28:21.160
We have time for maybe one question.

00:28:21.170 --> 00:28:29.690
Is there anyone in the audience

00:28:30.740 --> 00:28:36.160
with a question?

00:28:36.170 --> 00:28:37.160
Yes.

00:28:37.170 --> 00:28:38.160
Really interesting.

00:28:38.170 --> 00:28:39.160
Thanks.

00:28:39.170 --> 00:28:46.820
Do you have a sense for which primitives might be missing

00:28:46.820 --> 00:28:53.160
from the protocol right now to support this?

00:28:53.170 --> 00:28:58.150
And which are already there and useful?

00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:03.750
So, really, like, the biggest thing that is missing

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:08.520
is the permission data infrastructure, the one that has been proposed

00:29:08.520 --> 00:29:09.160
by Daniel.

00:29:09.170 --> 00:29:15.530
And the ability to connect infrastructure to existing, like, lists

00:29:15.530 --> 00:29:18.150
, for example, or credentials.

00:29:18.170 --> 00:29:22.970
I think that that infrastructure, that simple connection is really from

00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:25.160
where all of this can emerge.

00:29:25.170 --> 00:29:28.030
And a lot of the, like, the governance aspects of

00:29:28.120 --> 00:29:30.160
things, you know, for example, like the enforcing

00:29:30.170 --> 00:29:34.320
the ACLs and things like that, really come from the

00:29:34.320 --> 00:29:36.160
app level, right?

00:29:36.170 --> 00:29:39.550
And using metadata from within a post or, you know,

00:29:39.560 --> 00:29:43.160
whatever have you to actually compose this.

00:29:43.170 --> 00:29:46.420
But, you know, there's not really a ton that

00:29:46.420 --> 00:29:49.160
is missing here from the protocol.

00:29:49.170 --> 00:29:51.510
I think that once permission data happens and we have that credential

00:29:51.510 --> 00:29:56.280
infrastructure to work from, both, like, with a few

00:29:56.300 --> 00:30:00.970
record schemas, I think that this, that this can

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:04.160
be built.

00:30:04.170 --> 00:30:10.760
Well, I think this can be built without much additional infrastructure

00:30:10.760 --> 00:30:12.160
, you know?

00:30:12.170 --> 00:30:13.160
Thank you so much.

00:30:13.170 --> 00:30:16.150
Can we have one more round of applause, please?

00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:16.840
Thank you.
